Assignment Week 1: Do Americans Approve or Disapprove the Presidents Response to COVID-19?
Below youll find a dataset from fivethirtyeight.com titled How Americans View Bidens Response To The Coronavirus Crisis [https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/coronavirus-polls/]. Within the dataset there were a couple of csv files where I chose to look into two called covid_approval_polls.csv and covid_approval_polls_adjusted.csv. Both of these files look into Americans approval or disapproval of the way the US President is or has handled COVID-19, as well as a poll after adjustments were applied through a poll-averaging algorithm.
Explaination of columns in these datasets

  • subject: this column marks whose handling of COVID-19 the approval poll is about

  • party: party of respondents

    • R
    • D
    • I
    • ALL

  • startdate: start date of poll

  • enddate: end date of poll

  • pollster: organization that conducted the poll

  • sponsor: organization that sponsored the poll

  • samplesize: size of polling sample

  • population:

    • A for adults
    • RV for registered voters
    • LV for likely voters

  • tracking: True if the poll is a tracking poll, meaning that the pollster is releasing data with overlapping samples

  • text: text of the question the pollster asked

  • url: link to the poll

  • modeldate: date of model run

  • grade: grade given to the pollster(website below)

    • https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/pollster-ratings/

  • weight: weight given to each poll in the model

  • multiversions: __*__ denotes that multiple versions of a poll in the raw data file were combined

Conlcusion: After doing a minor analysis of these two data sets, I noticed minor changes from the original dataset to the adjusted one. For instance, with the approve ratings and approve adjusted, theres a decrease in the count from 600 to 500, while the disapprove ratings and disapprove adjusted were kept the same. When comparing the population and party from the first dataset with the population adjusted and party adjusted datasets I found one discrepency, v, which was not included in the original github description. The only ones accounted for are adults, registered voters and likely voters; regardless, there was only 1v" in both datasets, assuming its an outlier. In both graphs all the people who were surveyed were classified as adults with the least people classified as likely voters. Out of the adults plenty of them didnt fall under a particular political party and instead fell under all. Finally, when looking into the adjusted dataset, I looked to compare grades given and the party. In all parties, the highest ranking grade given was a B+, followed by B and B/C. The lowest ranking grade was C/D and A/B.

Moving forward Id update a couple of things such as, joining both datasets to have a better understanding of the data collected. Getting rid of n/a and missing cell values, especially when trying to calculate the mean and median for approve, disapprove, approve adjusted and disapprove adjusted. Lastly Id work with ggplot2 to create more interactive charts to analyze the data further.
